UPDATE 8.22.2019 : After many many many uses . . . minus a star because it doesn't catch all the coffee grounds so the coffee in pot is a little gritty. Minus another star because every once in a while the coffee is not evenly brewed. There are some dry spots in the grounds. My husband prefers the paper filters because paper filters works perfectly every time.

I bought this for my at-home coffee maker: the Hamilton Beach 2-Way Brewer, Model # 49980Z. I really like this HB Gold Tone filter for my coffee maker. It makes it super easy to remove the coffee grinds with its movable handle. Note: make sure the handle is down before shutting the lid on the brewer. I am excited that I no longer have to worry about the paper filter falling in on itself, this means that there are fewer grounds at the bottom of the coffee pot. I have only made a partial pot and the grounds stay in the basket. I don't know if the filter can handle the full 12 cup carafe with full strength coffee as we don't drink that much coffee here. The top of the filter is about 11 cm in diameter, the bottom of the filter is about 8.3 cm in diameter, height of filter is about 6 cm, the bottom of filter goes about 0.8 cm inward in the middle. This filter fits loosely in my coffee basket (there is a 2 to 3 mm gap if filter is pushed to one side), but it does not seem to jiggle while brewing. The black part of the filter is plastic. The copper tone part of the filter appears to be some sort of metal mesh. For care, I lightly hand wash with Dawn, rinse, and then air dry in dish rack. I am not a coffee connoisseur so I have no clue how it affects the flavor of my coffee; my coffee still tastes like coffee. Overall, I am very happy with this filter.

title: Best purchase on Amazon yet.
text:
Our 6 year old dryer was so loud it sounded like a freight train every time we spun it. Literally, while I was on the phone with my husband one day, I asked where he was because it sounded like he was driving somewhere next to a train track with a train going by. When he told me he was home, and I came home to see that he was sitting in the breakfast room (next to the laundry room), with the door closed and the dryer running. I was really surprised. I knew that the dryer was loud, but didn't realize it was THAT loud until I heard it over the phone. We had gotten used to it I guess.

Initially, I thought of buying a new dryer but then I came across some info about a quick and easy fix for loud dryers. I was unsure this was going to work but thought $40 bucks- no big deal. It took me two hours to fix it by myself but OMG was it worth it- especially considering the HOURS and HOURS of loud obnoxious dryer noises we've been listening to! Honestly, I may have been able to replace just ONE of the dryer rollers to fix it, but this kit came with almost everything that could possibly be the cause of loud noises. So I just replaced it all- JUST in case. Especially because I'd rather not have to take the dryer apart again! SOOOOO WORTH IT. Now, I actually forget that the dryer is even on. It worked THAT well- not even exaggerating.

Note: I'm a petite Mom (5'1" and 124lbs). Somewhat handy. and I was able to do it myself by watching/following YouTube videos. I find instruction manuals to be confusing so I like to watch YouTube- it took a couple different videos because there wasn't a thorough video on my specific dryer. But I followed them step-by-step and it was easy. The "heavy" parts were not that heavy IMO. However, I did have 2 hours of kid-free time. lol. And I even got to clean the lint from the dryer/lint container which has bothered me for quite some time.

title: So far 100% dust free
text:
If I could get rid of all the the flex duct, I would…if I could find flex duct that that wasn't thinner than tissue paper and more breakable than glass, I would. The problem is that is what is available.

So I searched for a way to eliminate bends, minimize the amount of flex, eliminate the possibility of clogging, and do everything I could to keep the lint and dust off the laundry room floor.

I liked the look of this product and with the exception of the depth of the fitting it worked perfectly. My dryer may be different than yours, but the frame of the dryer steps out (is deeper front to back) on the left side of the vent discharge. If the throat of the pipe had been a little longer or even perhaps adjustable (like pvc drain kits), then there would have been plenty of room and the dryer would not have interfered with the dust pipe . As you can see in the last picture, I had to place this piece on slightly at an angle. The part that allows the flex to attach to the elbow is brilliant. It softens the transition to the flex as well as prevent lint from escaping at the connection. The other thing this fitting does is extend back so that the flex pipe can't be crushed.

I used a simple elbow where the pipe passes through the exterior wall. Now the short flex duct is straight with no bends. I used foil tape to secure the ends of the flex. It's been a month or so, and so far no dust has escaped after numerous loads of clothes have run through the dryer.

This is definitely worth buying, and would be a 5 if the fitting was just a little longer. This project didn't take very long and will save me from moving the washer and dryer and cleaning all the lint off the floor.

title: Fixed my dishwasher
text:
Our dishwasher wouldn't drain. Replaced the old pump with this one, and now the dishwasher drains again.

Note, the pump we received is different from the picture, and different from the old pump. The old pump and the one in the picture have two permanently-connected white wires, but the received pump doesn't. Also, the old pump had a heavy piece of metal attached and the new one doesn't. However, the new pump does work well.

No instructions are included but the install is pretty straightforward. YouTube videos typically have you try to access the pump from under the dishwasher, but I found it was easier to kill power, turn off water, disconnect supply+drain, then pull out the dishwasher and put it on its side.

Initially I thought the wiring clip from the dishwasher wouldn't fit into the new pump, but then I found a cable that did. Not sure whether it was included with the new pump or if I'd taken it off of the dishwasher while disassembling. I did have to turn the cable around the opposite way to get it to plug in, vs. how the old pump was connected.

title: Part Specs Have Changed
text: This is the part # for our 11 year old GE refrigerator but this auger's measurements are different than the part I was replacing. I had bought another, cheaper auger on Amazon that also had problems with measurements. Other users recommended grinding down the metal rod.  I did not have a grinder so I returned that one. After installing this auger with all my original pieces it was binding some place. Couldn't see where. Auger would manually turn with extreme difficulty. I knew the motor could burn out if I reinstalled the housing it the way it was. I searched YouTube and checked the schematics for this part. My original auger had 2 metal washers plus a plastic spacer at the end closest to the plastic spirals.  Different schematics showed either 2 plastic spacers or 1 plastic spacer; no metal washers I finally found a couple on YouTube that demonstrated the difference in measurements on their auger.  They also had 2 metal washers. He was able to grind down the dent on the rod to allow all his original pieces to fit including the 2 metal washer. I was ready to return this auger as I did not have a grinder. I should not have to be a machinist to get a part to work. Taking a chance I put everything back on the rod in proper order except for the 2 metal washers. Everything works great. Ice cubes come out and cubes get crusher almost better than before.  Have been using for about a week without any problems. Very happy except this took me much more time to figure out than required. Without this issue it would have taken less than 20 minutes for total install and a 5 star rating. Something in the specs for this auger has changed over the last 11 years.

title: Correct Part Number, Wrong Rod Measurements
text: The part number sent was correct for the refrigerator model; however, the rod would need to be ground down in order for the original washers/spacers to fit on properly as others have noted.  I don't have a grinder and my attempts to modify with a wetstone were not successful.  I returned this part and ordered another auger, OEM, and paid twice as much but still had a similar issue.  Watched YouTube videos; checked schematics. My original auger had 2 metal washers plus a plastic spacer on the rod just before the plastic spirals started.  Schematics and videos showed 1 spacer or sometimes 2 spacers.  One YouTube video showed that the measurements were different between end of rod and the notch in the rod right before the plastic started.  Apparently there was a change in mfg specs at some point in time.  My refrig is 11 years old.  I couldn't make this part work and so returned it but managed to get the OEM auger to function by removing the 2 metal washers after seeing the YouTube video and checking the measurements.  I can now get ice cubes plus crushed ice.  Taking it apart and putting back together was not difficult but getting it to work properly was. May work fine for newer refrigerators.

title: Easy economical fix. Beats using a candle lighter.
text:
tl;dr - don't procrastinate. Easy economical fix to restoring sparks to burners. If I can do it, you can definitely do it!

Have had GE Stove since 1997.
Surface burners stopped lighting themselves 10 years ago.
Appliance repair was going to cost too much and decided to temporarily use a candle lighter.
Watched YouTube videos. Thought about fixing it myself.
5 years ago put this in my cart and then moved it to "Save for Later".
Bought at least 4 more candle lighters including the new USB plasma ones that works great.
1 year ago, oven stopped working. Luckily have combination micro/convection oven to bake things in, though tiny compared to full size oven. Microwave was installed too high so had to get on step ladder to safely use it as an oven.
2 months ago, decided to buy stove. Prices going up due to tarriffs. Didn't like price nor thinner sheet metal on newer stoves compared to the tank I bought 20+ years ago.
3 month ago, finally bought this part, "Used-Very Good" from volgacom. Took a gamble since part plus shipping was so much cheaper from volgacom vs new from Amazon with free shepping.
3 days later received good as brand new part. No signs of wear or use. SCORE!
Waited 2 more months. Though replacing this thing was going to be complicated.

Yesterday, decided to make repair. Didn't have to dismantle burners. as anticipated from YouTube videos.
Module is located behind control panel. 8 screws later, I was in. Only two wires to disconnect from old module and reconnect to new module. Snaps in place. Done. Put panel back together, restored power to stove.
First try, all burners spark and light as if the stove were brand new.

Will update review with longevity of part. Very happy with part and volgacom as the supplier. Like used parts not only saving money but also reducing carbon footprint.

title: I have ice again
text:
Unbelievable low price. Great delivery. Product works. Installed in ten minutes. Only problem that I faced was the ice maker had some cubes blocking rotation of the fingers and I could not align the shaft with the mating controller until I used a hair dryer to partially melt the cubes. That took about three minutes.

Gears on the synchronous motor jammed and that prevented the ice maker from cycling.

This control device has a puny looking synchronous motor compared to the original. See the attached pictures.

The rest of the story: I followed the advice to others by one of the repair/parts sellers on the Internet. The repair person gave assurance that the "no ice/no water to ice maker" problem would be solved by replacing the water dispenser/ice maker solenoid on the back side of the side-by-side. So, I spent the $80 on the solenoid and still no ice - no water to ice maker. Next, I did the emitter and receiver replacement thing. Still, no ice.

title: A replacement brand you can trust
text:
I'm one of those that usually prefers to buy the "name brand", especially when it comes to a water filter. The last house we lived in, we bought all new Frigidaire appliances, and I would only replace the fridge's water filter with PureSource replacements. Because the model was newer than what I have now, finding them on Amazon for a reasonable price wasn't hard.

However, that's no longer the case for the older Frigidaire I own now. Searching on Amazon for WF1CB or RG-100 turns up a ton of generic brands. The only PureSource options are from resellers at prices that cost 5-7 times more. Based on reviews, I decided to take a chance on Refresh. I'm definitely glad I did! The item came well-packaged and sealed in plastic. After installing the filter and running 4 gallons of water continuously through it (roughly 6-7 minutes), the water was coming out crystal clear. The chemical taste that was starting to develop under the old filter was gone, not a trace of it remained! The kids even commented that they noticed a big difference!

I went with the single pack this time around, but you can bet I'll be saving money on a 3-pack next time around, now that I know I can trust the brand. Buy with confidence!

title: Meets and exceeds expectations
text:
The item arrived exactly as described in its retail packaging. At first, there was a lot of air to purge from the system as I ran the recommended 5-6 gallons of water through the filter to prime it. Strangely, the water that first came out was greenish-blue in color. It didn't smell like other users reported in some of the negative reviews, but the first 32 ounces or so were definitely off-color. My refrigerator is about 9 months old, and this is the 1st time I've had to replace the filter. It doesn't seem like the original filter that came with the fridge did that, but maybe it did. Other than that initial hiccup though, seems to be functioning normal and I'm happy with the price.

Update (03/10/16):
Thought I'd provide an update. First, the water quality greatly improved after the first week. Six months later, I needed a replacement. After doing so from another listing, I noticed that the next one didn't have any issues when priming (no greenish-blue discharge this time). So I've dropped this one from 5 to 4 stars. No major issues, but not perfect.

Keep in mind that the suggested retail price of $73+ is bogus. Walk into any retail store that sells Frigidaire appliances, and you'll find this filter being sold for less than $50. Base the deal you're getting off of that.

text:
I am very impressed with this UV gel nail dryer. I do acrylic to my own nails and just got into gel polish. I purchased a top coat and base coat and then some color changing gel polish. This UV gel dryer is a great size and fits my whole hand inside. It comes with two settings: low and high, as you just press the button in the direction of which you prefer. The off button is in the center. The red button is the 120 second (2 minute) timer. You turn your device on and to whatever setting and press that button and it will turn the device off when done.

I applied a thin layer of base coat to my nail and let it cure for 2 minutes. Then I applied a thin layer of gel polish and let it cure for 2 minutes. I repeated the same step until I got the desired opacity. Afterwards, I touched it softly to see if the polish was dry and noticed it was very slightly still not dry (a light print of my fingerprint) so I put the top coat on and cured for about 5 minutes. It was completely dry by then, as I used thin coats and cured between so that it wasn't completely wet on bottom and dry just on top and smudge. I am very happy with this curing lamp, as it is my first. It is great quality plastic and the bottom of the inside of the lamp slides in/out for your convenience. It also comes with a US plug so no adapters needed. Just plug and play!

text:
Read the description carefully. These disposable coffee filters are for “Keurig, compatible with K Cup filter”. I assumed that they would work with non-Keurig single coffee machine reusable filter cups. I was wrong. They indeed do fit a reusable Keurig filter cup (See last photo)(I actually still have one from when I owned a Keurig). However, when I tried it with my CHEFMAN single coffee maker, the paper filter is too small, even with stretching out the sides. I ended up with a huge coffee mess when I opened the lid. I did tap the sides of the filter cup before opening, but coffee still went over the paper filter. For the most part, the cleanup was easier than without a paper filter. If the coffeemaker is not a Keurig, the paper filters won't fit exactly.

In Conclusion: Make sure you own a Keurig before ordering.

title: Powerful Electric Cooktop
text:
I ordered this simply for a couple of reasons: 1) Family likes cooking hot pot on special occasions and 2) Don't want to use our gas stove since we have solar. There are some positives and negatives for this cooktop. I used it for a week now and found that it has certain limitations.
What I Observed:
1) The actual cooking area is 8.25 inches in diameter. It takes ANY kind of material for your pots/pans, unlike induction cooktops which won't take certain material.
2) It heats up fast! I stir fried some veggies within 10 minutes. With that in mind, it gets hot fast. Would I buy this if I still had a toddler in the house? NO, unless I am constantly guarding it. The bottom and edge don't get hot, but the center glows red (which could be too intriguing for little kiddos)
3) The cord is only 31 inches long. We had to use an extension cord for hot pot at the table.
4) There are 5 settings: Warm, Lo, Medium, Hi, and Sear. There's a chart in the Instructions Manual of what each is capable of doing. I found that I only had to use the setting one below the recommended to get the job done.
5) One drawback of this electric cooktop is that it's Maximum Run time is ONE HOUR. After which you have to let it cool down before using again. It hampers when using for hot pot or if everything you're cooking takes longer than one hour. Hence, the 4 stars.
6) It is 120 V, 60 Hz, and 1200 W, pretty powerful. Maybe that's why you can only use it for one hour at a time.
7) One year warranty

My conclusion is that it's a good electric cooktop for fast cooking under an hour. Good as an extra burner. My son will inherit this when he goes to college. The price is very reasonable.

Back to Ready Joe, this time coupled with an electric kettle.  I was disappointed that, unlike other Melita plastic filter cones, this one did not indicate it was BPA-free.  Maybe it is, or maybe it is impossible to make it both red and BPA-free. Vaguely unsettling. #4 filers work best, as does pouring only a small amount of water over the grounds to let it bloom before pouring the rest of the water in (also helps keep the water from draining through the grounds and filer too fast.) After seven months, with regular washing in the dishwasher and less regular by hand, it looks slightly faded and scratched (maybe I should worry more about BPA). I don't find the view hole particularly helpful -- maybe it would work if I poured the water while sitting at the kitchen table.  As it is -- a tall person standing at the kitchen counter --- I have to  do some special contortions to view the coffee level in the cup. Not worth it. But it is cheerful, convenient, and poses less danger to barely-awake coffee-makers than do other methods.

text:
It's lovely to look at if you leave it on the counter. It's simple to use just filled with grounds and pour in water. You don't need to use a paper filter with it -- so not extra paper to throw away. There's a bit at the bottom that makes sure there no to very little grounds to get in your coffee (it the grind is very fine there's usually leakage) medium grind it best.

Lots of the previous reviews said it was easy to clean -- it is slightly easier than cleaning my French Press. Let the grounds dry a bit, turn upside down over trash bin and give a couple of hits, then use your pointer finger to run around the inside and push what's clinging to the sides and very bottom into the trash. Then rinse out and wash your hands of grounds. No extra paper used and cleaned filter ready to reuse.

Since it had sat for 2 days without making ice (instructions call for cleaning if sitting w/o making ice for more than two days) Inwas cleaning the machine with my normal routine of vinegar & after a bit of bleach on q-tips for hard to reach nooks/crannies. I and noticed the q-tips would have a tan substance while I was drying around the lil hole perforated square price in bottom right corner (where the water gets pulled up through a tube or channel to the top in order to start the ice making process). I wondered if I could detach it and it popped out, I got nauseous when I saw what was under it, hidden away. I sprayed a bit of bleach kitchen cleaner in the area and after a few seconds I took a q-tip to it and around the hole where the water enters and almost vomited when it looked like a bunch of stringy snot on the end of the q-tip🤢. I had to keep going over & over it w/q-tip and each time I pulled it up more & more came out🤢. I have been queasy ever since, all I can think about is put clean, filtered water in the tank but that was useless because it was being pulled through that hole/tube/channel I order to get the after to the top where the lil freezing cones are. Of course the return window has closed because Amazon uses the date the first defective machine was ordered not the date the replacement was sent so I guess the $109 I spent hoping for fast, clean ice will go straight to the recycling center or to the dump. Sorry for the bad review but I have to be honest while at same time send a warning to others who own this same machine (probably other ice machines as well). text: We've had K-cup coffee on and off for many years. We have certainly added our share of non-compostable waste to the landfill. Not too proud of that. However, we tried the reusable filters along the way and were unimpressed. The metal mesh technology of years ago was so coarse that the coffee was impossible to drink near the bottom of the cup. The problem I've run into with both the BrewRite and Melitta is that new filters tenaciously stick to each other at the crimped edges. To totally solve the problem, I put the filters in a plastic 6"x4" card box (see the picture I've added above). Once the filters have set on edge for a while, they tend to relax their grip.

text:

No doubt about it, being able to increase the measure of coffee...and the better distribution of the water, made all the difference. Though I've enjoyed the Solofill experience for the most part, there was just no way I could get around it's physical limitations. I worked very hard to perfect a process that ran good beans, a good grind, and filtered water through the Solofill. However, the generally so-so to good cups of coffee never rose to greatness. Same as everyone else, once I get through my stock of fridge filters, I hit up AMazon to order more. First I check what I orderd last time (in this case "ClearChoice Taste"), and tehn see if I can get more/better for my money. I read the specs on this Waterdrop and decided it was a better price for teh features I wanted. I looked though the reviews and saw teh occasional problem with slow water flow. So, when I got them I looked at the hole on top (some users said it was smaller). See the pics. At first blush, it looks smaller, but if you look inside (to the black part) they are the same size where the water goes in.
Same as with other filters I prefill it before installing it. Manufacturers make no mention of this, but it helps avoid all that sputtering and splashing until the air is out. Once installed, I timed the flow for 1 liter. 15 seconds in my fridge - exactly the same as the old filter (well, at least out to the second). Good enough for me. Water looks clear, and tastes ok. It is nto well water, so I'm mostly doign this becuase I think it filters out chlorine (in reality probably does not)

title: A pain in the butt to install, but worth the effort
text:
I had a slow leak coming from my ice maker. I "knew" it was a soleniod problem, but chose to try lowering the valve pressure. Of couse this didn't help, and I kept dealing with huge blocks of ice in the ice maker, and a waterfall of ice down the back of the freezer. I blew that off too. Eventually, the ice mass in the ice bucket froze to the auger, and when someone asked for ice it broke the auger. Yes, I turned a one part job into a two part job...
Came here and orderd soleniod and auger. Soleniod is a quick install (like 10 minutes - more if your wife wants to clean under the fridge) and I was back in business there. Auger took a lot longer, but now I have ice and no drip problems. I went with the legit part and not a knockoff becuase I have tried knockoff parts on other repairs and it tends to be hit or miss (cheap parts sometimes break sooner). If your bothing to do the work and save the labor cost, may as well go with good parts. This auger takes a beating, so you want something that will hold up (or you will find bits of broken platic in your drink - like I did with the old one.
